  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements designed to combat money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Global standard-setting body for anti-money laundering policies\n- Provides guidelines for 39 member countries\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Requires member states to criminalize money laundering\n- Promotes international cooperation in investigating and prosecuting money laundering\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision Guidelines\n- Sets international banking standards to prevent financial crime\n\n4. European Union's Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Establish uniform regulations for EU member states\n\n5. Bank Secrecy Act (U.S.)\n- Requires financial institutions to assist government agencies in detecting and preventing money laundering\n\nThese frameworks typically require countries to:\n- Criminalize money laundering\n- Implement reporting requirements for financial transactions\n- Establish regulatory oversight\n- Facilitate international information sharing\n- Develop mechanisms for asset seizure and recovery\n\nWhile specific implementation varies by country, these international standards provide a comprehensive approach to combating money laundering globally.",
